	(16729,546,'wpcf-short-description','An interactive installation that investigates the cross-modal relationship between expectations and actual sensations'),
	(16730,546,'wpcf-long-description','The following scenario was conceptualized aiming to manipulate the audiences’ expectations and then surpass them. \r\n\r\nVisitors come into a dimly-lit room and see a water tank placed on a low table. They walk closer to the tank and look down into the tank from above. Suddenly, they notice vapor emerging from the surface of the water in the tank. They realize that the vapor is glowing, illuminated by the LEDs from below the surface. They then notice that their portraits are being projected by the LEDs onto the mist.  As they move around in front of the tank, the image corresponds to the movement because their motion is captured in real time by a camera mounted on the edge of the tank. They become curious and intrigued and move even closer to the tank. They might even try to touch the portrait. The visitors might blow the mist away. In short, as they interact with the vapor, they are also interacting with their own image.'),
